[h1]Variables Scope[/h1]

PHP variables can be declared anywhere in the script.
The [b]scope[/b] of a variable is the part of the script in which the variable can be referenced or used.

PHP's most used variable scopes are [b]local[/b], [b]global[/b].
A variable declared outside a function has a [b]global scope[/b], and can only be accessed outside of a function.
A variable declared within a function has a[b] local scope[/b], and can only be accessed within that function.

Consider the following example.[code format="php" codeId="488"]<?php
  $name = 'David';
  function getName() {
    echo $name;
  }
  getName();

  [b]// Error: Undefined variable: name[/b]
?>[/code]
This script will produce an error, as the[b] $name[/b] variable has a [b]global[/b] scope, and is not accessible within the [b]getName()[/b] function.
[note][b]Functions[/b] will be discussed in the coming lessons.[/note]

quizzes.question:
What output results from the following code?
<?php 
$num1 = 56;
function  my_func() {
  $num1 = 89;
  echo $num1;
}
my_func();
?>

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The global Keyword[/h1]

The [b]global [/b]keyword is used to access a global variable from within a function.
To do this, use the [b]global[/b] keyword within the function, prior to the variables.[code format="php" codeId="467"]<?php
  $name = 'David';
  function getName() {
    [b]global $name;[/b]
    echo $name;
  }
  getName();

 [b] //Outputs 'David'[/b]
?>[/code]
